<h2 class="govuk-heading-l">Technical information about this website’s accessibility</h2>

<p class="govuk-body">
    DVSA is committed to making its website accessible, in accordance with the Public Sector Bodies (Websites and
    Mobile Applications) (No. 2) Accessibility Regulations 2018.
</p>

<p class="govuk-body">
    This website is partially compliant with the <a
            title="external link to Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 2.1" class="govuk-link" target="_blank"
            href="https://www.w3.org/TR/WCAG21/">Web Content Accessibility Guidelines version 2.1</a> AA standard, due
    to the non-compliances listed below.
</p>

<h2 class="govuk-heading-l">Non accessible content</h2>

<p class="govuk-body">
    The content listed below is non-accessible for the following reasons.
</p>

<h3 class="govuk-heading-m">Non compliance with the accessibility regulations</h3>

<p class="govuk-body">
    The following areas of non-compliance exist.
</p>

<p class="govuk-body">
    Postcode fields, select elements, table headers and some checkboxes are unlabelled which means that users with
    impaired vision will not know what should be entered into these fields. The country select field does not make the
    auto-complete functionality clear to screen readers. This does not meet WCAG 2.1 success criterion 1.3.1
    (Information and Relationships). We plan to fix this by March 2021.
</p>

<p class="govuk-body">
    Some list items are not contained within a <dl> parent element. This will interfere with the way that screen
    readers interact with the page content and will make it more difficult for users to understand the structure of the
    information presented. This does not meet WCAG 2.1 success criterion 1.3.1 (Information and Relationships). We plan
    to investigate and fix this by March 2021.
</p>

<p class="govuk-body">
    Some pages and documents do not have a level one heading. This impacts users of screen readers. This does not meet
    WCAG 2.1 success criterion 1.3.1 (Information and Relationships). We plan to fix this by March 2021.
</p>

<p class="govuk-body">
    Some input fields have ambiguous labels for screen readers because the fieldset and legend markup have not been
    properly used. This does not meet WCAG 2.1 success criterion 1.3.1 (Information and Relationships). We plan to fix
    this by March 2021.
</p>

<p class="govuk-body">
    Non-editable pdfs exist at certain parts in the user journey. These are not accessible. This does not meet WCAG 2.1
    success criterion 1.3.1 (Information and Relationships). We plan to fix this by March 2021.
</p>

<p class="govuk-body">
    On some pages, the focus order of the page does not follow the expected task sequence.  This does not meet WCAG 2.1
    success criterion 1.3.2 (Meaningful Sequence). We plan to fix this by March 2021.
</p>

<p class="govuk-body">
    Some status indicators have a low colour contrast ratio. This does not meet WCAG 2.1 success criterion 1.4.3
    (Contrast Minimum). We plan to fix this by March 2021.
</p>

<p class="govuk-body">
    The focus indicator contrast is not sufficient for some users. This does not meet WCAG 2.1 success criterion 1.4.11
    (Non-text contrast). We plan to fix this by March 2021.
</p>

<p class="govuk-body">
    The time out rules mean that users may be timed out before they have finished some task sequences. This does not
    meet WCAG 2.1 success criterion 2.2.1 (Timing adjustable). We plan to investigate and fix this by March 2021.
</p>

<p class="govuk-body">
    On some pages, the focus order does not follow the natural task sequence. This does not meet WCAG 2.1 success
    criterion 2.4.3 (Focus Order). We plan to fix this by March 2021.
</p>

<p class="govuk-body">
    Some tables cannot be accessed using swipe gestures on mobile devices. This does not meet WCAG 2.1 success
    criterion 2.4.3 (Focus Order). We plan to fix this by March 2021.
</p>

<p class="govuk-body">
    Some links are not descriptive including document type, ‘remove this’ This does not meet WCAG 2.1 success
    criterion 2.4.4 (Link Purpose). We plan to fix this by March 2021.
</p>

<p class="govuk-body">
    Action buttons and headings do not make it clear to screen reader users which object the action will be applied to.
    This does not meet WCAG 2.1 success criterion 2.4.6 (Headings and Labels). We plan to fix this by March 2021.
</p>

<p class="govuk-body">
    The select element used in address look-up does not function as expected with arrow keyboard controls. This does
    not meet WCAG 2.1 success criterion 3.2.2 (On Input). We plan to fix this by March 2021.
</p>

<p class="govuk-body">
    In some places, the in-line error text is ambiguous. This does not meet WCAG 2.1 success criterion 3.3.3 (Error
    Suggestion). We plan to fix this by March 2021.
</p>

<p class="govuk-body">
    When multiple items of the same type are added, duplicate field IDs are used. This causes screen readers to report
    the field as unlabelled. This does not meet WCAG 2.1 success criterion 4.1.1 (Parsing). We plan to fix this by
    March 2021.
</p>

<p class="govuk-body">
    The custom control ‘More actions’ menu button within the vehicles pages does not announce its state to screen
    readers, and the keyboard access to this control is not as expected.  This does not meet WCAG 2.1 success criterion
    4.1.2 (Name, Role, Value). We plan to fix this by March 2021.
</p>

<p class="govuk-body">
    Under some conditions, buttons and controls such as table sorting are hidden from screen readers. This does not
    meet WCAG 2.1 success criterion 4.1.2 (Name, Role, Value). We plan to fix this by March 2021.
</p>

<p class="govuk-body">
    Some status changes such as the ‘new’ flag for directors are not announced to screen readers. This means some users
    are unaware of new content on the page. This does not meet WCAG 2.1 success criterion 4.1.3 (Status messages). We
    plan to fix this by March 2021.
</p>

    <h2 class="govuk-heading-l">How we tested this website</h2>

    <p class="govuk-body">
        This website was last tested on 13-17 January 2020 by The Digital Accessibility Centre (DAC).
    </p>

    <p class="govuk-body">
        We used this approach to decide a sample of pages to test:
    </p>

    <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
        <li>our highest volume transaction (vehicle changes)</li>
        <li>all sections of the ‘Manage my licence’ user journey (which duplicates the main pages of the ‘Apply for a
            licence’ journey
        </li>
        <li>journeys we know cause problems for users (change operating centre and vehicle authorisation, reviewing the
            submission)
        </li>
        <li>links to external pages containing further advice</li>
        <li>critical pages underpinning compliance (the document/correspondence section of the website)</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="govuk-body">
        Our public search pages and internal caseworker pages were tested internally using GDS guidance and insights
        from the independent accessibility audit conducted by DAC.
    </p>

